<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="6ee974cf4de38a06044ad0beed948577" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> A Mathematician&#39;s View: Critical Hits<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.80)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/swtcg/main/mpage.php?member=10789'>Chris "McLarenC" McLaren</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/swtcg/main/mpage.php?member=10789&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 28, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> 	This is the second article in my third series of articles on the Star Wars TCG.  Of course my first series covered the different themes of cards that exist in the game, and the second series, which will continue concurrently with this one, covers different elements that can be manipulated or controlled in the game such as force or build points and deck manipulation.  This article looks further into the mathematical nature of this card game and builds on the first by looking at the concept of critical hit.  <br />
	Now my last article looked at how to tell how likely it was to get a certain number of hits with a certain number of dice.  Now I am going to look at how the expected number of hits is affected by the addition of critical hits to the mix.  Now of course critical hits can vary in degree, generally from 1 to 3, in how much additional damage they do.  Now rolling one die it is easy to determine how often you will get a critical hit, you need to roll a six to get a critical hit, so this becomes 1/6th.  Now of course calculating out what you would expect in the way of hits, say this is a critical hit 3, you would expect .5 hits (1/2*1) from the regular roll of the dice and .5 hits (1/6*3) from the critical hit each time add them together and you get the expected value of 1 hit per turn.  Now this may work for 1 die, but if it were that easy, I would not have written an article on it.  <br />
	When you get to 2 dice it gets more complex.  Of course we know how to get the expected number of hits without the critical hit, it is one.  We also know the probability distribution as well.  But how does the critical hit affect this?  Sticking with the critical hit of 3 we can add the probability of rolling a 6 on one die times the number of dice minus the probability of rolling a 6 on both of these dice. So we add 1/6*2 and subtract 1/36, then multiply this number by the critical hit factor of 3 to get an expected critical hit of 11/12.<br />
	Now three dice gets even more complex.  The 1/6th is now multiplied by 3 (the number of dice), the 1/36 is now multiplied by 3 as well (the number of sets of 2 dice), and then we need to add back in 1/216 cause we have now taken it out too many times all to get 91/216.  Then multiple by the factor of 3 for the critical hit to get 91/72  And four or five dice gets even worse.  Is there a mathematical solution to this problem?<br />
	Do you think that I would have written this article if there was not a mathematical solution to it?  Of course, there is a solution to it.  Actually, it is quite simple.  The problem that we are running into is the fact that we have to take into account if we get multiple sixes on dice.  In the case of two dice, we are looking at them separate and then taking out the extra occurrence if it happens on both dice.  This is what causes the extreme complexity when we get to four and five dice and beyond.  What if we look at the probability that we dont get a six on the dice, this is the probability that we do not get a critical hit, the complementary event.  We know that either this event or the other has to happen, so we can move back and forth between the probability of the two events.<br />
What is the probability of not rolling a six on one die?  It is 5/6, of course 1-5/6=1/6.  So the probability that we were originally looking for is 1 out of 6, which is the probability of a critical hit with one die.  Now looking at 2 dice, we again raise 5/6 to the power of the number of dice we are rolling and then subtract it from one: 1-(5/6*5/6)=1-(25/36)=11/36, which again is the probability of a critical hit with 2 dice.  And as a final example, 3 dice: 1-(5/6)^3=1-(125/216)=91/216, again the answer we were looking for.<br />
	Below is a list with the probability of a critical hit given rolling up to 12 dice (for those who dont want to do the math):<br />
<br />
1 : 16.67%<br />
2 : 30.56%<br />
3 : 42.13%<br />
4 : 51.77%<br />
5 : 59.81%<br />
6 : 66.51%<br />
7 : 72.09%<br />
8 : 76.74%<br />
9 : 80.62%<br />
10 : 83.85%<br />
11 : 86.54%<br />
12 : 88.78%<br />
<br />
	So when calculating the expected number of hits on a unit with a critical hit, take one half the power and add the above percentage times the critical hit factor, and that will give you a true measure of what to expect that unit to get as far as go.  <br />
	But what do you do if you want to find the distribution for the number of hits that a unit is likely to get?  Is it as simple as adding an amount to the table given in the last article?  Unfortunately, it is not as simple.  You have to take into account the fact that if I tell you that you hit rolling on die, I also tell you something about the likelihood of there also being a critical hit.  Initially there was a one in six chance of a critical hit, but by telling you there was a hit, I have told you that you did not roll a 1,2, or 3.  Likewise, if I told you that there was a critical hit on a roll of six dice you would know that there was at least one hit rolled and that would tell you something about the dice as well.  Statistically this is called independence, or in this case lack of independence.  <br />
	So what can be done to construct a table that would include critical hits in the probability distribution for the total amount of damage done?  Well first off if I tell you the number of hits, what is the probability of a critical hit?  As seen above, the probability of a critical hit goes from one in six to one in three.  So we can re-state the probability of a critical hit as 1-(2/3)^H, where H is the number of hits that were achieved.  This will let us construct a distribution based on finding the probability of there being a critical hit to add to the total number of hits or not.  For example, with a critical hit of 3 and rolling 2 dice we would find the probability distribution like so:<br />
Find the standard distribution as in the last article {2:(25.00%,50.00%,25.00%)}<br />
	For each of the &quot;hit levels&quot; find the probability of a critical hit {2:(0.00%,16.67%,30.56%)}<br />
	Multiply each of the probabilities from the first step by the probability of the critical hit to find the &quot;critical hit increase&quot; then take the difference between the two to find the probability that remains at that level.  <br />
	Shift the first set by the critical hit factor and then add it to the first, giving us the distribution for the total number of hits.  It it a pretty complex task, but also fairly simply once you pick it up.  And easy to execute on a spreadsheet.  <br />
<br />
	For a critical hit of one the hit distribution looks as such:<br />
<br />
1:(50.00%,33.33%,16.67%)<br />
2:(25.00%,33.33%,27.78%,13.89%)<br />
3:(12.50%,25.00%,29.17%,24.54%,8.80%)<br />
4:(6.25%,16.67%,25.00%,28.24%,18.83%,5.02%)<br />
5:(3.13%,10.42%,19.10%,26.62%,25.08%,12.95%,2.71%)<br />
6:(1.56%,6.25%,13.54%,22.28%,26.62%,20.04%,8.28%,1.43%)<br />
7:(0.78%,3.65%,9.11%,17.22%,24.64%,24.10%,14.73%,5.03%,0.74%)<br />
8:(0.39%,2.08%,5.90%,12.56%,20.79%,24.82%,19.95%,10.16%,2.96%,0.38%)<br />
9:(0.20%,1.17%,3.71%,8.77%,16.41%,22.99%,22.81%,15.38%,6.69%,1.69%,0.19%)<br />
10:(0.10%,0.65%,2.28%,5.91%,12.30%,19.70%,23.17%,19.39%,11.20%,4.25%,0.95%,0.10%)<br />
11:(0.05%,0.36%,1.37%,3.88%,8.85%,15.90%,21.57%,21.52%,15.48%,7.81%,2.63%,0.53%,0.05%)<br />
12:(0.02%,0.20%,0.81%,2.49%,6.17%,12.24%,18.77%,21.71%,18.68%,11.75%,5.26%,1.59%,0.29%,0.02%)<br />
<br />
	For a critical hit of 2 it looks like this:<br />
<br />
1:(50.00%,33.33%,0.00%,16.67%)<br />
2:(25.00%,33.33%,11.11%,16.67%,13.89%)<br />
3:(12.50%,25.00%,16.67%,16.20%,20.83%,8.80%)<br />
4:(6.25%,16.67%,16.67%,15.74%,22.07%,17.59%,5.02%)<br />
5:(3.13%,10.42%,13.89%,14.47%,20.45%,22.40%,12.54%,2.71%)<br />
6:(1.56%,6.25%,10.42%,12.38%,17.65%,23.23%,18.95%,8.14%,1.43%)<br />
7:(0.78%,3.65%,7.29%,9.92%,14.52%,21.40%,22.42%,14.29%,4.99%,0.74%)<br />
8:(0.39%,2.08%,4.86%,7.52%,11.48%,18.27%,22.90%,19.18%,9.99%,2.94%,0.38%)<br />
9:(0.20%,1.17%,3.13%,5.45%,8.77%,14.79%,21.19%,21.78%,15.03%,6.62%,1.69%,0.19%)<br />
10:(0.10%,0.65%,1.95%,3.80%,6.49%,11.49%,18.26%,22.05%,18.88%,11.06%,4.22%,0.95%,0.10%)<br />
11:(0.05%,0.36%,1.19%,2.57%,4.67%,8.64%,14.91%,20.53%,20.89%,15.24%,7.75%,2.62%,0.53%,0.05%)<br />
12:(0.02%,0.20%,0.72%,1.69%,3.28%,6.33%,11.68%,17.92%,21.05%,18.34%,11.64%,5.23%,1.58%,0.29%,0.02%)<br />
<br />
	And for a critical hit of 3 this it what it looks like:<br />
<br />
1:(50.00%,33.33%,0.00%,0.00%,16.67%)<br />
2:(25.00%,33.33%,11.11%,0.00%,16.67%,13.89%)<br />
3:(12.50%,25.00%,16.67%,3.70%,12.50%,20.83%,8.80%)<br />
4:(6.25%,16.67%,16.67%,7.41%,9.57%,20.83%,17.59%,5.02%)<br />
5:(3.13%,10.42%,13.89%,9.26%,8.29%,17.77%,21.99%,12.54%,2.71%)<br />
6:(1.56%,6.25%,10.42%,9.26%,7.75%,14.26%,22.13%,18.81%,8.14%,1.43%)<br />
7:(0.78%,3.65%,7.29%,8.10%,7.22%,11.28%,19.72%,21.99%,14.25%,4.99%,0.74%)<br />
8:(0.39%,2.08%,4.86%,6.48%,6.44%,8.96%,16.35%,22.13%,19.01%,9.98%,2.94%,0.38%)<br />
9:(0.20%,1.17%,3.13%,4.86%,5.45%,7.15%,12.99%,20.16%,21.44%,14.97%,6.62%,1.69%,0.19%)<br />
10:(0.10%,0.65%,1.95%,3.47%,4.38%,5.68%,10.05%,17.14%,21.54%,18.73%,11.03%,4.22%,0.95%,0.10%)<br />
11:(0.05%,0.36%,1.19%,2.39%,3.36%,4.46%,7.65%,13.87%,19.90%,20.65%,15.18%,7.74%,2.62%,0.53%,0.05%)<br />
12:(0.02%,0.20%,0.72%,1.59%,2.48%,3.44%,5.76%,10.83%,17.26%,20.72%,18.23%,11.62%,5.23%,1.58%,0.29%,0.02%)<br />
<br />
	Notice how as the critical hit increases the number or possible hits increases as well.  Especially evident is when one die is rolled the probability of rolling no hits stays the same, the probability of one hit is the probability of a hit times the probability of not getting a critical hit, and then wherever 1+ the critical factor would be the rest of the probability falls.  Notice also, how it stretches the distribution out and what it does to the mean (highest probable value on the graph) of the distribution, at lower powers there are essentially two modes.<br />
	It is amazing how a little twist like adding a critical hit increases the complexity of the game incredibly.  Hopefully my explanations were understandable and the mathematics beneficial.  If you do have any questions, feel free to ask, and look for the next topic in this series: the setup phase.<br />
